passages.text: Sales Remain Impressive; Investments Limiting Flow Through

2Q comps +5% were a solid beat vs cons +3%, underscoring DKS's position as a market share winner in athletic. EPS of $4.38 also beat Visible Alpha cons of $4.28, while the flow-through from the comp beat to EPS was underwhelming. While mgmt raised F25 guidance by ~$0.10, accounting for a stronger 2Q and moderately higher 2H comp assumptions, they guided 3Q EPS down yr/yr (vs cons +LSD), suggesting higher investments are continuing to limit profit flow-through. While we expect DKS to continue to deliver upside to their comp guidance in 2H, upside to EPS seems more limited, given this dynamic. With the FL deal closing on 9/8, there is much to learn about mgmt's views around the impacts on F26 EPS from the combined DKS+FL and investments needed in FL to turn around the business, making the outlook more uncertain. We see a balanced risk/reward at current levels.

**Ests & TP:** We are lowering our F25/F26E from $14.53/15.35 to 14.37/15.27 driven by lower GM/higher SG&A, which is offsetting our higher 2H comp assumptions. We are maintaining our $225 TP, which implies an F26E EV/EBITDA multiple of 8.0x and an F26E P/E multiple 14.0x.

**Incremental info from mgmt follow-up:** (1) Mgmt expects 2H merch margins and gross margin to expand at a slightly greater rate than the 35bps in 1H; (2) Mgmt called out a $10M donation of footwear in 4Q LY (25bps headwind to GM in 4Q) that they are lapping this year, which helps support 2H merch margin expansion; (3) Mgmt emphasized many favorable tailwinds to merch margin (Gamechanger, media network, favorable product/category/brand mix, pricing), but acknowledged they built in a little more markdown pressure in 2H vs their prior guidance to account for a dynamic and promotional environment; (4) Not seeing much non-comp lift despite sq footage growth and HOS & Field House openings, given most store conversions from a regular store to a HOS/Field House store drive higher sq footage (store footprint expansion), but are not considered new stores, so included in comp base; (5) Mgmt did not commit to SG&A leverage if on a +LSD comp in F26, but said they expect to leverage SG&A at +LSD comp over time; (6) 75-80% of 2H pre-opening expenses will fall into 3Q; (7) Vertical brands #2 largest brand behind NKE in apparel.

Dick's Sporting Goods was founded by Richard ("Dick") Stack in 1948. It was formerly known as Dick's Clothing and Sporting Goods, Inc. and changed its name to Dick's Sporting Goods, Inc. in 1999. The company is headquartered in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Dick's sells sporting goods equipment, apparel, and footwear. The company's sales breakdown is approximately \(45\%\) hardgoods (equipment), \(35\%\) apparel, and \(20\%\) footwear. Equipment categories include exercise and team sports (i.e., treadmills and lacrosse sticks), outdoor recreation (i.e., guns, hunting/fishing gear, kayaks), and golf.

We rate DKS a Neutral. DKS is a leader in the sporting goods channel, and a valuable partner to the most important brands in athletic apparel and footwear. After making strategic investments in omni- channel capabilities, DKS emerged from the Covid pandemic in a much stronger position, allowing it to take advantage of market share up for grabs in the industry. With DKS's sales base \(\sim \$ 3.5bn\) higher than pre- pandemic levels, we believe it will be more difficult for DKS to expand sales and EPS over the next few years, making the risk/reward more balanced at current levels.
Our DCF- based \(225TP\) is based on a \(12\%\) discount rate and a \(\sim 7.5x\) terminal multiple on year- 5 EBITDA. Our target price implies an F26E P/E multiple of \(\sim 8.8x\)

Macro uncertainty. The company's results have not been consistent over the past several years, and they have been playing under the umbrella of a strong consumer. If the consumer were to weaken, the company's sales and profits could be negatively impacted. Conversely, if the macro environment improves more than expected, sales/profits could be positively impacted.
Supplier risk. DKS relies on key name brands to drive revenues. If any major supplier decided to stop supplying DKS with its product, we would expect it to have a negative impact on DKS revenues.

Declining traffic trends. DKS stores are located in both enclosed malls and off- mall locations. Over the last several years, DKS has faced declining traffic trends. Additionally, DKS stores are extremely large, averaging \(\sim 50k\) sq feet. If traffic declines were to deteriorate further, DKS could be forced to downsize and/or close more stores, which could negatively impact sales and profits.

Fashion risk. While the athletic footwear and apparel category tends to rely less on fashion to drive demand relative to other categories, fashion is still a consideration when consumers purchase athletic footwear and apparel. If DKS products do not meet the expectations of their customers, DKS could face pressure to revenue and profits.

Brand support: If DKS gets access to better product from its most important brands, there is potential it could grow sales/margins beyond what we currently expect, which would be a positive for the stock. If the impact on the company from any of these factors proves to be greater or less than we anticipate, the stock will either outperform or underperform our target price.
